---
import ClerriLayout from '../../layouts/ClerriLayout.astro';
---
<ClerriLayout title="LinkedIn Series · Month 1" section="linkedin-series">

<div class="page-head">
  <div class="page-eyebrow">Channels & Budget · Ready-to-Post Copy</div>
  <h1 class="page-title">Month 1 LinkedIn series — <em>"the insurance escape is real."</em></h1>
  <p class="page-sub">14 posts for the awareness wave. Founder-led (8x the reach of the company page), 3-4x/week. Copy is written to ship — tune one line to voice and schedule. Hooks are built to survive the "…see more" cutoff.</p>
</div>

<div class="page-body">

  <div class="takeaway">
    <span class="tk-lbl">Bottom line</span>
    <p>Most posts run from <strong>Jim's profile</strong> (CEO owns positioning + gets the reach); 3 are written for <strong>your</strong> profile (new-leader POV); a couple flex to a team voice. The first line is everything on LinkedIn — that's the only part that shows before the fold, so each is engineered to stop the scroll. Reply to every comment in the first 2 hours; that's what the algorithm rewards.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="progress-track"><div class="progress-fill" data-progress-fill="linkedin-series"></div></div>
  <p class="mono" style="font-size:0.75rem;color:var(--muted)">Posts shipped: <span data-progress-here="linkedin-series">0 / 0</span></p>

  <div class="callout wine">
    <div class="lbl">Before you post</div>
    <p style="margin:0">The customer/MRR stats (45→715 members; $1,276 vs $469; 51% lift) are Kleer/vendor-sourced — <strong>verify the real customer + numbers before they headline a post.</strong> And patient-side framing stays informational (anti-kickback) — these B2B posts target dentists/owners/DSOs, which is clean.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Week 1 — <em>open the narrative.</em></h2>

  <div class="post">
    <div class="post-meta"><span class="tag">Post 1</span> <span class="who">Jim (CEO)</span> <span class="fmt">Text · POV</span></div>
    <p>Dentists don't have an income problem. They have an insurance problem.</p>
    <p>You didn't spend 8 years and six figures of debt to argue with Delta over 55 cents on the dollar.</p>
    <p>But that's the job now for too many owners — chasing reimbursements, eating write-downs, letting a spreadsheet at insurance HQ decide what your work is worth.</p>
    <p>Here's what most miss: it's not "accept the PPO" OR "go cash-only and scare off your patients." There's a third door. A membership plan lets you take your practice back — one patient at a time — while keeping the patients you already have.</p>
    <p>The dentists thriving right now aren't the ones with the most chairs. They're the ones who stopped letting insurance rent space in their operatory for free.</p>
    <p>What's the #1 thing insurance costs you that has nothing to do with money?</p>
  </div>

  <div class="post">
    <div class="post-meta"><span class="tag">Post 2</span> <span class="who">Jim (CEO)</span> <span class="fmt">Carousel · 8 slides</span></div>
    <p><strong>Hook slide:</strong> "The $3-6M most dentists never realize they gave away."</p>
    <p><strong>Slides:</strong> (2) Over a 30-year career, the average practice writes off $3-6M to PPO adjustments. (3) That's not a line item. That's a second home / your kids' college / retiring 5 years earlier. (4) You don't see it because it leaves 12% at a time. (5) Meanwhile a membership patient produces ~$1,276/yr vs ~$469 for the uninsured. <span class="vmono">(verify)</span> (6) And completes 5.9 procedures/yr vs 2.4. (7) Membership doesn't replace insurance overnight — it starts clawing the margin back, patient by patient. (8) CTA: "Run your own number → [calculator link when live]."</p>
  </div>

  <div class="post">
    <div class="post-meta"><span class="tag">Post 3</span> <span class="who">Jerris (you)</span> <span class="fmt">Text · Intro/POV</span></div>
    <p>I just stepped in to lead marketing at Clerri. Three weeks in, here's the thing I can't unsee:</p>
    <p>Dentistry is having its "cut the cord" moment.</p>
    <p>~35% of dentists say they're planning to drop a PPO. 37 state insurance-reform laws passed last year alone. The dam is cracking — and most practices have no plan for what comes after the insurance check stops covering the gap.</p>
    <p>The ones who'll win aren't going cash-only and praying. They're building a membership base <em>now</em>, while they still have the insured volume to convert.</p>
    <p>I'm going to be sharing what I learn about this shift in the open. If you run or manage a practice and you're wrestling with the insurance question — I want to hear where you actually are. Comment below.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Week 2 — <em>the data + the trend.</em></h2>

  <div class="post">
    <div class="post-meta"><span class="tag">Post 4</span> <span class="who">Jim (CEO)</span> <span class="fmt">Text · Data</span></div>
    <p>A membership patient is worth 2.7x an uninsured one. Most practices treat them the same.</p>
    <p>$1,276 a year vs. $469. 5.9 procedures vs. 2.4. And practices that build a real membership base see a ~51% lift in cash production over two years. <span class="vmono">(verify)</span></p>
    <p>The uninsured patient isn't a low-value patient. They're an <em>un-converted</em> one. The 70M+ Americans with no dental coverage aren't a hard market — they're an underserved one that pays cash and rewards practices who make access simple.</p>
    <p>The question was never "will they pay?" It's "who makes it easy enough for them to say yes?"</p>
  </div>

  <div class="post">
    <div class="post-meta"><span class="tag">Post 5</span> <span class="who">Jim or Jerris</span> <span class="fmt">Poll</span></div>
    <p>Honest question for practice owners:</p>
    <p>If you could drop your worst PPO tomorrow — no patient loss, no revenue dip — would you?</p>
    <p><strong>Poll options:</strong> "Tomorrow." / "If I had a safety net." / "No, I need the volume." / "Already did it."</p>
    <p>(First comment from you: "The 'safety net' answer is the whole game. That's exactly what a membership base is — here's how practices build one before they drop a plan.")</p>
  </div>

  <div class="post">
    <div class="post-meta"><span class="tag">Post 6</span> <span class="who">Jim (CEO)</span> <span class="fmt">Text · Story</span></div>
    <p>One practice went from 45 members to 715 in 24 months. Their recurring revenue went from $1,575/mo to $25,025/mo. <span class="vmono">(verify customer + numbers)</span></p>
    <p>They didn't hire a sales team. They didn't retrain the front desk into closers. They made joining the plan so simple a patient could do it at checkout in under a minute.</p>
    <p>That's the part people get wrong about membership. It's not a sales problem. It's a friction problem.</p>
    <p>Remove the friction — at the chair, at checkout, online — and enrollment compounds quietly in the background. Recurring revenue that doesn't depend on a payer's fee schedule.</p>
    <p>What's the biggest friction point stopping your patients from saying yes?</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Week 3 — <em>myth-bust the objection.</em></h2>

  <div class="post">
    <div class="post-meta"><span class="tag">Post 7</span> <span class="who">Jim (CEO)</span> <span class="fmt">Text · Myth-bust</span></div>
    <p>"But won't I lose patients if I push a membership plan?"</p>
    <p>It's the first thing every dentist asks me. Here's the honest answer: no — because membership isn't cash-only, and it isn't instead of insurance.</p>
    <p>It runs <em>alongside</em>. It's the safety net for the patients you'd otherwise lose — the ones who just dropped their coverage, the ones who never had it, the ones a competitor down the street is about to make an offer to.</p>
    <p>The practices that lose patients aren't the ones with a membership plan. They're the ones who made a patient choose between "use insurance" and "pay full freight" — and watched them walk.</p>
    <p>You set the fee schedule. You keep the relationship. That's the opposite of losing patients.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="post">
    <div class="post-meta"><span class="tag">Post 8</span> <span class="who">Jim (CEO)</span> <span class="fmt">Text · Contrarian</span></div>
    <p>Unpopular opinion: "just go cash-only" is terrible advice for most dentists.</p>
    <p>It's the advice that gets shared on every FFS podcast, and for a small number of established practices in the right market, it works. For everyone else it's a cliff.</p>
    <p>Going cold-turkey cash-only means betting your schedule that patients will pay full price with zero structure. Most won't — not because they can't, but because nothing made it easy or predictable for them.</p>
    <p>Membership is the bridge the "go cash-only" crowd skips. Predictable monthly value for the patient, recurring revenue for you, and a path off insurance dependence that doesn't require a leap of faith.</p>
    <p>Don't jump off the PPO cliff. Build the bridge first.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="post">
    <div class="post-meta"><span class="tag">Post 9</span> <span class="who">Jim (CEO)</span> <span class="fmt">Carousel · 6 slides</span></div>
    <p><strong>Hook slide:</strong> "30% of dentists dropped a PPO last year. Here's what separated the winners from the regretters."</p>
    <p><strong>Slides:</strong> (2) The regretters dropped the plan and hoped. (3) The winners built a membership base <em>first</em>. (4) Winner move #1: convert before you cut — enroll uninsured + soon-to-lapse patients while you still see them. (5) Winner move #2: make enrollment frictionless (chairside, checkout, online). (6) Winner move #3: structure it compliantly so it survives a state audit (more on that this week). CTA.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Week 4 — <em>the DIY wedge + the enterprise angle.</em></h2>

  <div class="post">
    <div class="post-meta"><span class="tag">Post 10</span> <span class="who">Jim (CEO)</span> <span class="fmt">Text · The real competitor</span></div>
    <p>Your in-house membership plan might be illegal. And almost nobody selling you on "just DIY it in a spreadsheet" will mention that.</p>
    <p>In most states, a dental membership plan is a regulated product. Run it wrong — no DMPO licensing, the wrong patient agreement, a discount structure that trips anti-kickback rules — and you're exposed to fines, or worse, a shutdown.</p>
    <p>The "I'll just build my own" plan feels free. The liability isn't.</p>
    <p>This is the part of the membership conversation that doesn't make it onto the podcasts: the structure matters as much as the offer. Doing it on a platform that carries the compliance load isn't a convenience — it's the risk transfer that lets you sleep at night.</p>
    <p>If you run an in-house plan today: when's the last time anyone checked it against your state's rules?</p>
  </div>

  <div class="post">
    <div class="post-meta"><span class="tag">Post 11</span> <span class="who">Jim (CEO)</span> <span class="fmt">Text · DSO/Data</span></div>
    <p>We surveyed 105 dental leaders — mostly groups and DSOs. One number reframed everything for me:</p>
    <p>96% said 10-30% of their patients are uninsured or underinsured. But only 19% have a standardized way to capture that revenue.</p>
    <p>For a 25-location group, a 10% attrition rate on those patients is roughly $10M in lost lifetime revenue. Not from a market problem — from an <em>infrastructure</em> problem.</p>
    <p>The single-location version of this is a missed opportunity. At DSO scale, it's a strategy gap your board should be asking about.</p>
    <p>Full benchmark dropping soon. DSO leaders — does that 19% match what you see internally?</p>
  </div>

  <div class="post">
    <div class="post-meta"><span class="tag">Post 12</span> <span class="who">Team voice (CS or office-mgr champion)</span> <span class="fmt">Text · Office-manager angle</span></div>
    <p>Your front desk spends more time fighting one insurance claim than it would take to enroll five members.</p>
    <p>Office managers know this better than anyone. The benefit verifications. The preauths. The denials. The "do you take my insurance?" calls. It's the least glamorous, most time-eating part of the job.</p>
    <p>Here's what nobody tells you: a strong membership base doesn't just add revenue — it <em>subtracts</em> work. Fewer claims to chase. Patients who show up. Money that lands without a 45-day fight.</p>
    <p>The practices with the happiest front desks aren't the ones with the best insurance contracts. They're the ones who depend on insurance the least.</p>
    <p>Office managers — what's the one insurance task you'd erase from your day forever?</p>
  </div>

  <div class="post">
    <div class="post-meta"><span class="tag">Post 13</span> <span class="who">Jim (CEO)</span> <span class="fmt">Text · Emotional/Story</span></div>
    <p>A dentist told me last month: "Leaving Delta felt like ending a bad marriage. I stayed way too long because I was scared of what came after."</p>
    <p>That line stuck with me, because it's the real reason most practices don't change — not the economics, the fear.</p>
    <p>Fear that the patients won't follow. Fear that the schedule empties out. Fear that you traded a known frustration for an unknown one.</p>
    <p>But here's what she found on the other side: patients who chose <em>her</em>, not her network status. Revenue she could predict. And a practice that finally felt like hers again.</p>
    <p>The fear is real. It's also the only thing standing between a lot of great dentists and the practice they actually want.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="post">
    <div class="post-meta"><span class="tag">Post 14</span> <span class="who">Jim or Jerris</span> <span class="fmt">Text · Soft conversion</span></div>
    <p>For the dentists and office managers who've been DM'ing me about where to start —</p>
    <p>We built a quick calculator that shows what your practice is actually leaving on the table with PPO write-offs, and what a membership base could recover. No demo, no sales call — just your numbers. <span class="vmono">(link when live)</span></p>
    <p>And the full 2026 Dental Membership Benchmark — what 105 dental leaders told us about the cash-pay opportunity — drops next week. Comment "benchmark" and I'll send it when it's out.</p>
    <p>You don't have to fire your insurance company tomorrow. But you should know exactly what it's costing you to keep it.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>How to run it</h2>
  <div class="grid-3">
    <div class="card"><h4>Cadence</h4><p style="font-size:0.875rem">3-4 posts/week across 4 weeks. Tue/Wed/Thu land best. Space the carousels (Posts 2, 9) a week apart — they carry the most reach.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><h4>Engagement</h4><p style="font-size:0.875rem">Reply to every comment within ~2 hrs. The first-comment "extension" (Posts 5) keeps people in-thread. Founder voice &gt; brand page every time.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><h4>Feeds the funnel</h4><p style="font-size:0.875rem">Posts drive to the calculator + benchmark report (the gated MOFU assets). Boost the best 2-3 organic posts as Thought Leader Ads (6.4x the CTR of single-image).</p></div>
  </div>

  <div class="note-block">
    <div class="note-label">LinkedIn series notes <span class="note-saved">✓ saved</span></div>
    <textarea data-note="linkedin-series-notes" placeholder="Which posts performed, hooks to reuse, comments worth turning into posts, which to boost as TLAs..."></textarea>
  </div>

  <div class="topic-foot">
    <a href="/clerri/content-ecosystem"><span class="dir">← Prev</span><span class="name">Content Ecosystem</span></a>
    <a href="/clerri/messaging-playbook"><span class="dir">Next →</span><span class="name">Messaging Playbook</span></a>
  </div>

</div>

<style>
  .post { background:#fff; border:1px solid var(--cotton-dark); border-radius:0.9rem; padding:1.1rem 1.25rem; margin:0 0 1rem; }
  .post-meta { display:flex; gap:0.5rem; align-items:center; margin-bottom:0.6rem; flex-wrap:wrap; }
  .post-meta .tag { background:var(--clerri-green); color:var(--zest); font-family:'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size:0.65rem; padding:0.15rem 0.5rem; border-radius:1rem; }
  .post-meta .who { font-weight:700; font-size:0.8rem; color:var(--clerri-green); }
  .post-meta .fmt { font-size:0.72rem; color:var(--muted); font-family:'JetBrains Mono', monospace; }
  .post p { font-size:0.92rem; line-height:1.5; margin:0 0 0.55rem; }
  .post p:last-child { margin-bottom:0; }
  .vmono { font-family:'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--muted); }
</style>

</ClerriLayout>
